<DOC><DOCNO> AP880810-0261 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2339EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hostages     08-10 0302</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Hostages,0312</SECOND><HEAD>Church Leader Holds Secret Hostage Talks, Report Says</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An Iranian official met Archbishop of CanterburyRobert Runcie in secret talks in London Wednesday to discussBritish hostages in Lebanon, the British domestic news agency PressAssociation reported.   The reported 75-minute meeting followed other recent contactsbetween church officials and the Iranian government and signs ofimproving relations between Britain and Iran. The 18 foreignhostages in Lebanon are believed held by pro-Iranian groups.   Press Association said Church of England officials arranged ameeting with Mohamed Reza Said Mohamedi, an Iranian ForeignMinistry official based in Tehran, at Lambeth Palace, Runcie'sofficial London residence. Runcie is spiritual leader of the Churchof England.   The agency said no details about the meeting were disclosed, butthat it was believed the discussions included the fate of Runcie'sspecial envoy, Terry Waite; television journalist John McCarthy andteacher Brian Keenan.   Waite vanished in Beirut on Jan. 20, 1987, while seeking therelease of American and other foreign hostages. No group claimedresponsibility for his disappearance.   McCarthy was kidnapped on April 17, 1986.   Keenan has been missing since April 11, 1986. Keenan fromBelfast, Northern Ireland, holds dual British and Irishnationality, and the Irish government is also seeks his release.   The longest-held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle Eastcorrespondent for the Associated Press, who was taken captive March16, 1985.   John Lyttle, a senior adviser to Runcie, who was in Tehran inJune for talks with Iranian religious and government officials,also attended Wednesday's meeting, the agency said. It said Lyttleconfirmed Mohamedi met with Runcie Wednesday but said Lyttledeclined to give details.   On Monday, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's governmentannounced it will send a British diplomat to Iran this week for thefirst time in a year.</TEXT></DOC>